Two investment firms have taken a “substantial interest” in software maker Primavera Systems as part of a recapitalization of the company, the firms and Primavera announced on Monday.

Terms of the investment from Francisco Partners and Insight Venture Partners were not disclosed, but an article from The Daily Deal– in which Primavera Systems founder and chief executive Joel Koppelman is quoted — said company insiders sold 75 percent of their shares for “more than $150 million.” Among those selling their stakes in the transaction was Intel Capital, the venture capital arm of chip giant Intel, The Daily Deal reported.

Founded in 1983, Primavera makes project management software for the construction, energy and other industries.

